class RideSharingSystem {
    private LinkedHashSet<Integer> riderSet;
    private LinkedHashSet<Integer> driverSet;

    public RideSharingSystem() {
        riderSet=new LinkedHashSet<>();
        driverSet=new LinkedHashSet<>();
    }
    
    public void addRider(int riderId) {
        riderSet.add(riderId);
    }
    
    public void addDriver(int driverId) {
        driverSet.add(driverId);
    }
    
    public int[] matchDriverWithRider() {
        int isDriverAvailable=!driverSet.isEmpty()?driverSet.getFirst():-1;
        int isRiderAvailable=!riderSet.isEmpty()?riderSet.getFirst():-1;
        if(isDriverAvailable==-1 || isRiderAvailable==-1)
            return new int[]{-1,-1};
        driverSet.removeFirst();
        riderSet.removeFirst();
        return new int[]{isDriverAvailable,isRiderAvailable};
    }
    
    public void cancelRider(int riderId) {
        if(riderSet.contains(riderId))
            riderSet.remove(riderId);
    }
}



Time Complexity (TC)
addRider(int riderId): O(1)
Adding an element to a LinkedHashSet takes constant time on average because it internally uses a hash table.
addDriver(int driverId): O(1)
Same as addRider, inserting into the LinkedHashSet takes constant time.
matchDriverWithRider(): O(1)
Using Java 21's getFirst() and removeFirst() on a LinkedHashSet takes constant time. This is because LinkedHashSet maintains a doubly-linked list behind the scenes, allowing it to instantly peek at or remove the head node in O(1) time without needing to iterate.
cancelRider(int riderId): O(1)
Checking .contains() and calling .remove() by value both use the underlying hash table lookup, taking constant time on average.

Space Complexity (SC)
Overall Space Complexity: O(R + D)
Where R is the number of active riders currently waiting in the system and D is the number of available drivers.
Each unique ID stored inside riderSet and driverSet consumes memory proportional to the number of elements actively kept in the system. Canceled or matched entries are fully removed from memory.

